00:32:40.210 --> 00:32:45.389
stay and right outside is -- that's the mountain
on which the telescopes have

00:32:45.389 --> 00:32:50.629
been built. You can barely see the domes at
the top and these are the four, uh,

00:32:50.629 --> 00:32:54.519
telescopes, uh, call -- that make up the Very
Large Telescope. So each

00:32:54.519 --> 00:33:01.680
telescope is 8.2-meter primary mirror and
at the time that they were built --

00:33:01.680 --> 00:33:05.809
and even now -- they're -- they're among the
largest, uh, telescopes in

00:33:05.809 --> 00:33:10.490
existence and especially four in such close
proximity. There's nowhere else on

00:33:10.490 --> 00:33:15.690
earth you'll find these such telescopes. Umm,
you -- you might recall the, umm,

00:33:15.690 --> 00:33:21.970
uh, earthquake in Chile recently and you will
wonder why they would build such

00:33:21.970 --> 00:33:27.090
fancy equipment in, uh, in places like Chile.
Well, obviously the skies are

00:33:27.090 --> 00:33:30.360
wonderful which is why they want to build
them but at the same time you have to

00:33:30.360 --> 00:33:34.460
deal with earthquakes. And this mirror -- this
is one of the mirrors of the

00:33:34.460 --> 00:33:39.879
VLT -- you can see that shiny bit, that's
8.2 meters across and it's 18

00:33:39.879 --> 00:33:45.279
centimeters thick and the whole thing weighs,
just the mirror, weighs about 23 tons.

00:33:45.279 --> 00:33:50.779
And it's so heavy and, uh, relatively thin
compared to its diameter that as the

00:33:50.779 --> 00:33:55.460
telescope is moving, uh, sort of from zenith
to our horizon and back and forth

00:33:55.460 --> 00:33:58.889
the mirror is going to warp a bit because
the gravitational force is moving on a

00:33:58.889 --> 00:34:03.870
change as it, uh, it changes orientation.
And that's enough to change the shape

00:34:03.870 --> 00:34:08.360
of the mirror enough to mess up your observations.
So actually underneath the

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:13.079
mirror there are about a 150 pistons that
are constantly pulling and pushing at

00:34:13.079 --> 00:34:17.040
the mirror to keep it in shape. So essentially
the mirror is not anchored.

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:20.659
It -- it's floating on these pistons so if
an earthquake were going to happen it

00:34:20.659 --> 00:34:24.309
would just rattle around and break, you know?
There's no -- nothing holding it.

00:34:24.309 --> 00:34:28.200
But the amazing thing is that you can't see
it very clearly in this picture but

00:34:28.200 --> 00:34:31.929
there are clamps all the way around the periphery
of the mirror and the moment

00:34:31.929 --> 00:34:36.300
they sense a tremor, these clamps hold on
to the mirror, 23 tons of it, and just

00:34:36.300 --> 00:34:40.800
lift it right off the supports and just anchor
it to the superstructure. And

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:43.900
then the superstructure is designed to just
sway with the earthquake. So the

00:34:43.900 --> 00:34:48.080
idea then is that the mirror is not going
to rattle around and it's just going

00:34:48.080 --> 00:34:53.289
to, you know, if the earthquake is not severe
 -- if it's severe enough to damage

00:34:53.289 --> 00:34:57.619
the superstructure that's another thing but
for most earthquakes this will work

00:34:57.619 --> 00:35:03.069
and it has worked in the past. Umm, let me
just, uh -- so the reason I went to

00:35:03.069 --> 00:35:10.270
see the VLT was to understand. I mentioned
dark matter. We don't understand what,

00:35:10.270 --> 00:35:14.690
about 90 percent of the matter in the universe
is made of, but about a

00:35:14.690 --> 00:35:19.740
decade ago astronomers were looking at, uh,
what I call the supernovae, type one

00:35:19.740 --> 00:35:24.950
supernovae which are just stars that are dying
and they were using these stars

00:35:24.950 --> 00:35:29.670
to figure out how the expansion of the universe
has changed over time. You

00:35:29.670 --> 00:35:34.000
know, Hubble found out that the universe is
expanding, uh, since the Big Bang

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:38.810
and then the -- the expectation among, uh,
physicists was that this expansion

00:35:38.810 --> 00:35:42.441
should now be slowing down because the gravity
of the matter in the universe

00:35:42.441 --> 00:35:46.880
should be, uh, starting to pull back the universe
in a sense. So if you were to

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:51.990
observe how the expanse -- expansion rate
is progressing in the recent past, say

00:35:51.990 --> 00:35:55.700
the last few billion years, the idea was that
this expansion rate should be

00:35:55.700 --> 00:36:00.200
slowing down and they found exactly the opposite,
that in the last, uh, few

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:03.130
billion years the expansion of the universe
instead of slowing down is actually

00:36:03.130 --> 00:36:07.900
speeding up. Something is blowing apart the
universe and that something turns

00:36:07.900 --> 00:36:14.020
out is the energy of space time itself, that
the vacuum of space, meaning

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:18.820
everything. This, where we are standing, this
is also vacuum of space. You

00:36:18.820 --> 00:36:23.470
know, in between galaxies. Essentially all
of the universe is contained in this

00:36:23.470 --> 00:36:29.059
vacuum of space and that fabric of space time
has some energy and when they

00:36:29.059 --> 00:36:32.270
total up how much energy that is, it turns
out to be about 3-quarters of the

00:36:32.270 --> 00:36:38.710
matter and energy in the universe. So this
pie chart -- now I can show this

00:36:38.710 --> 00:36:45.540
happily to a technology crowd without getting
gasps. But, uh, that's our view

00:36:45.540 --> 00:36:50.470
of the universe now. We have dark energy which
is 73 percent, we have dark

00:36:50.470 --> 00:36:54.660
matter which is about 23 percent, and normal
matter 4 percent. So all our

00:36:54.660 --> 00:36:58.690
theories so far in physics, theories that
have been verified and confirmed in

00:36:58.690 --> 00:37:04.990
experiments can only be vouched for 4 percent
of the matter. The rest of the

00:37:04.990 --> 00:37:08.580
universe, 96 percent of the universe, is a
mystery. Mystery of source. We have

00:37:08.580 --> 00:37:13.119
theories but really we have no experimental
evidence to tell us what dark matter

00:37:13.119 --> 00:37:16.350
is, we don't really understand dark energy.
There are many outstanding

00:37:16.350 --> 00:37:21.270
questions about where this, uh, energy of
the fabric of space time comes from,

00:37:21.270 --> 00:37:25.140
has it changed over time, you know, how will
it effect the universe in the

00:37:25.140 --> 00:37:28.910
future, things like that and we really don't
know. So the whole point of this

00:37:28.910 --> 00:37:32.810
book was to basically visit various experiments
that are going to start answering these

00:37:32.810 --> 00:37:37.569
questions. And so the big questions, what
is dark matter, what is dark

00:37:37.569 --> 00:37:42.470
energy? Uh, I've just spoken about that. The
other two big things is, uh,

00:37:42.470 --> 00:37:47.579
reconciling quantum mechanics with Einstein's
General Relativity. And quantum

00:37:47.579 --> 00:37:50.920
mechanics we know works really well. It's
been verified endlessly by

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:55.160
experiments but it works at things at the
microscopic level and Einstein's

00:37:55.160 --> 00:37:58.480
General theory of relativity same thing. It's
been verified really well but

00:37:58.480 --> 00:38:02.800
it's a theory of gravity on cosmological scales,
so for large distances. There

00:38:02.800 --> 00:38:06.640
are situations in physics where these two
things have to be combined. Take the

00:38:06.640 --> 00:38:10.750
Big Bang. Uh, the Big Bang the universe was
supposed to be smaller than a

00:38:10.750 --> 00:38:16.619
proton if you can imagine that and -- but
at the same time all of the energy of

00:38:16.619 --> 00:38:21.619
the universe was compressed in a tiny volume
so it had extremes of gravity. So

00:38:21.619 --> 00:38:26.079
you need Einstein's relativity to deal with
gravity but you need quantum

00:38:26.079 --> 00:38:29.610
mechanics to deal with the microscopic volumes
and, uh, when you put these two

00:38:29.610 --> 00:38:32.650
together, they don't work. So you have two
pillars of modern physics,

00:38:32.650 --> 00:38:37.119
relativity and quantum mechanics, that work
beautifully on their own but

00:38:37.119 --> 00:38:40.570
whenever you need to bring them together they
don't. And so there is this

00:38:40.570 --> 00:38:44.150
question to find this theory of what's called
quantum gravity so I talk about

00:38:44.150 --> 00:38:47.530
that in the book. And then there's the physics
beyond the standard model. I --

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:52.150
I talked about how 4 percent of the universe
can be explained. Well, most of

00:38:52.150 --> 00:38:54.760
that can be explained by this thing called
the standard model of particle

00:38:54.760 --> 00:38:58.210
physics which is essentially a theory of all
of the particles of matter,

00:38:58.210 --> 00:39:02.200
electrons, protons, neutrons, all of that,
and the forces that act upon them,

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:07.691
all except gravity and it's a very well-tested,
uh, theory, the standard model

00:39:07.691 --> 00:39:11.760
of particle physics and we know there has
to be things beyond that because

00:39:11.760 --> 00:39:15.390
standard model cannot explain dark matter
for instance, it doesn't have much to

00:39:15.390 --> 00:39:19.190
say about dark energy, it cannot reconcile
quantum mechanics with relativity.

00:39:19.190 --> 00:39:22.400
So we know that there is physics beyond it.
So again the experiments are

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:26.810
beginning to provide us clues about that.
